Happy winter solstice!  Thawing out at 3am post winter surf session while working on the @sweatpantsmedia @chrisburkard 'Under An Arctic Sky' film.  Lots of suffering involved going out in -20 degree temps at night in Icelandic winter so it was crucial to have these cabins to recover in! ~

For me it was a cool little window into surf culture.  I've heard surfing is bit more territorial and less inclusive than climbing. But from my limited experience the lifestyles and camaraderie is so similar - especially at the exploratory fringes.  Check out www.UnderAnArcticSky.com for more on the film for more on this project. Featuring @heidarlogi @timmyreyes @jquinny @taylorfreesolo @zellnerdy @hogstine @benweiland @arcticsurfers @ellithor ~ #wintersolstice

For those who are curious more about my art process, each one of these pieces was created as part of the climbing life: ~ ‚ÄúBefore Renan was a filmmaker, he spent his days doing landscape painting while climbing. Renan spent years living in a tent beneath the desert walls of Utah and the snowy Himalayan mountains, carrying large swaths of raw cotton canvas on his back to the places he cut his teeth as a professional climber. He uses mixed media, found materials, oil pastels, watercolors, acrylics, ink pens and even natural pigments pulled straight from the earth to capture these wildly beautiful landscapes. All of his paintings were created on expedition, right in the dirt beneath towering mountains, securing the canvases and stitched papers to the ground with heavy stones. These paintings are impressionistic, vividly colorful, and acutely contoured with details that mirror the jagged ridges and dramatic skis that Renan experienced while pushing the bleeding edge of alpinism and art. 
His canvases are worn, folded, and wrinkled with the dirt of the mountains. Each of these large canvases and papers he carried on his back rolled up into his pack, sometimes for over 100 miles, to the base of his climbs. The cracked paint, dried from the sweeping alpine winds, is an imprint of the weathering forces of nature that Renan endured on these expeditions. The paintings are a literal embodiment of the adventure itself.‚Äù (Words by Taylor)
